questions.text: Given histology pic is of which of the following?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (B)

Fibro Cartilage

Fibrocartilage is the tough, very strong tissue found predominantly in the intervertebral disks and at the insertions of ligaments and tendons; it is similar to other fibrous tissues but contains cartilage ground substance and chondrocytes.

questions.text: Area marked in the given image is supplied by dermatome number?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (C)

T10

The marked dermatome which includes the umbilicus is supplied by T10.

The dermatomal distribution of the abdominal region is as follows:

• T7, T8, T9 - supplies skin from the xiphoid process to just above the umbilicus.

• T10 - supplies skin around the umbilicus.

• T11, T12- supplies skin below the umbilicus upto the suprapubic region.

• L1 - supplies skin around the genitalia and upper medial thigh.

questions.text: The arrow in the image denotes which of the following muscles?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (A)

Extensor carpi radialis longus

The arrow shows extensor carpi radialis longus. It originates from the distal third of the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserts at the second metacarpal (radial side). It is in radial nerve, C6, and C7.

questions.text: The cell marked in the below slide is inhibitory to
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (A)

Deep nuclei of cerebellum

The structure marked in the image is a flask-shaped neuron in the cerebellar cortex, which is a Purkinje cell. It is Inhibitory to deep cerebellar nuclei.

Purkinje cells are the flask-shaped cells present in the Purkinje cell layer of the cerebellum. They are evenly spaced and arranged in a single layer between molecular and granular cell layers. The dendrite from each cell passes upward to enter the molecular layer and the axon of each cell passes downwards, crosses the granular cell layer, and terminates on the deep cerebellar nuclei. They are inhibitory and use GABA as their neurotransmitter

questions.text: Identify the papillae from the given histological section.
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (B)

Circumvallate

The given histological image is a section of the tongue showing circumvallate papillae, the largest papillae of the tongue. Circumvallate papillae are large cylindrical structures that are around 8-12 in number, covered by non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium.

questions.text: A 38-year-old man had recently joined a gym to improve his physical health. He attempted to lift a 30 Kg dumbbell but developed sudden pain in his right arm. He came to the casualty with an abnormal bulge over his arm as shown in the image below. Which of the following tendons is most likely to be injured?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (C)

Proximal tendon of biceps

The above image shows the Popeye sign, which is seen in the proximal biceps tendon rupture. Popeye sign is seen on flexing the elbow. An extremely prominent bulge of the muscle belly occurs as its unrestrained fibers contract. The proximal biceps tendon makes up 90-97% of all biceps tendon ruptures. In isolation, it has little effect on the upper limb function but produces a characteristic deformity called the Popeye sign.

questions.text: Identify the structure(s) in the following histological image.
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (D)

Glomerulus

The above histology image shows the glomerulus.

Glomerulus is a rounded tuft of anastomosing capillaries lined by fenestrated endothelium. Blood enters the tuft through an afferent arteriole and leaves it through an efferent arteriole. It is supported by the mesangium containing mesangial cells and a non-cellular mesangial matrix.

questions.text: What does the area marked X overlie?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (C)

2nd, 3rd, and 4th tracheal cartilage

The structure marked X is the isthmus of the thyroid gland. It overlies 2nd, 3rd, and 4th tracheal rings. Isthmus connects the lower parts of both the lobes of the thyroid gland. It is usually present anterior to the 2nd and 3rd tracheal cartilages, but the position may vary according to its size.

questions.text: To what level of vertebrae does the marked structure correspond?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (D)

At the junction of L3 & L4

The structure marked in the given image is the umbilicus and it corresponds to the level of the junction between the third and fourth lumbar vertebrae (L3 & L4). However, the skin around the umbilicus is supplied by the thoracic spinal nerve T10 (T10 dermatome).

questions.text: Identify the anatomical structure marked in the given image.
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (D)

Extensor pollicis longus

The marked structure in the given image is extensor pollicis longus.

The name “snuffbox” originates from the use of this surface for placing and then sniffing powdered tobacco, or “snuff.

Anatomical snuffbox boundaries:

Lateral wall: Abductor pollicis longus (APL), Extensor pollicis brevis (EPB)

Medial wall: Extensor pollicis longus (EPL).

Roof: Cephalic vein, Sup. Br of radial nerve

Floor: Radial styloid, Scaphoid, Trapezium and 1st Metacarpal.

questions.text: Which of the following arteries is palpated in the image shown below?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (B)

Posterior tibial artery

The posterior tibial artery is palpated between the medial malleolus and the calcaneal tendon, as shown in the image. The posterior tibial artery can be felt by keeping the foot relaxed between plantar and dorsiflexion and palpating against the distal tibia behind and below the medial malleolus, approximately one-third of a line connecting the posterior border of the medial malleolus to the calcaneal tendon (Achilles tendon).

choices.text: From the dorsal rami of C1

questions.text: The muscle marked by arrow in the image below is innervated by the:
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (A)

Dorsal scapular nerve

The muscle marked in the above image is levator scapulae, which is innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve.

questions.text: The structure marked A in the image below gives rise to which of the following structures?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (C)

Falciform ligament

The structure marked A is ventral mesentery. The falciform ligament is a derivative of the ventral mesentry.

questions.text: The following finding was noted in the twins that were delivered a couple of hours ago. Identify the condition.
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (D)

Pygopagus 

The image shows conjoined twins with fusion in the sacral region, which is known as the pygopagus.

In monochorionic monoamniotic twinning, incomplete duplication of the embryonic disc can occur. Incomplete separation of the monozygotic twins results in the birth of two infants that are joined or fused together at some part of the body. These twins are known as conjoined twins or Siamese twins.

choices.text: Sensation in the anterior scalp and dorsum of the nose

questions.text: If a tumor compresses the structures passing through the opening marked in the given image, which of the following sensations would be affected?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (C)

Sensation in the anterior scalp and dorsum of the nose

The marked foramen is the superior orbital fissure. If a tumour compresses the structures passing through this foramen, it would impair sensation in the anterior scalp and dorsum of the nose, as this would affect the frontal nerve and nasociliary nerve.

questions.text: What is the outer covering of the condition shown in the image?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (B)

Amnion

The diagnosis based on the given image is omphalocele and is covered by the amnion.

Omphalocele is a midline abdominal wall defect where the bowel and other solid viscera protrude through the umbilicus. In this condition, the herniated organs are covered by both peritoneum and an amnion. The umbilical cord inserts directly into this sac, which helps in identifying the condition. The defect occurs due to the failure of the physiological hernia to return to the body cavity by the 11th week of gestation.

questions.text: A patient presented with a fracture of the structure marked below following a road traffic accident. Which of the following symptoms will be seen in this is patient?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (A)

Anosmia

The structure marked in the given image is the cribriform plate of the ethmoid and fracture to the cribriform plate will lead to anosmia as the olfactory nerve fibres pierce through it.

questions.text: Identify the labelled structure:
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (B)

Internal capsule

The labelled structure is the Internal capsule.

questions.text: Identify the liver segment marked in the image below.
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (A)

VIII

The highlighted liver segment is segment VIII.

A horizontal plane known as the portal plane divides the liver where the portal vein bifurcates and becomes horizontal. This divides each section of the liver into superior and inferior segments:

- Left lateral section: segment II above and segment III below the portal plane

- Left medial section: segment Iva above and segment IVb below the portal plane

- Right anterior (or medial) section: segment VIII above and segment V below the portal plane

- Right posterior (or lateral) section: segment VII above and segment VI below the portal

questions.text: Blood supply of the marked structure in the given specimen is derived from which of the following artery?
questions.solution:
Correct Answer (C)

Anterior cerebral artery Marked part is fornix Most of medial surface supplied by anterior cerebral artery. Fornix is supplied by anterior cerebral > internal carotid & posterior cerebral artery.
